{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170963/1937090901/0503.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL NEWS\nThe Business Trend\nResting On Backlogs\nThe stock market In August reg\nistered the largest net decline for\nany month since July, 1934, but did\nnot quite descend to the low of the\npresent year. Bond averages showed\na smaller net loss. Trading on the\nstock exchange was characterised by\nack of vitality, but a loss of 61*\npoints in one month was sufficient to\n\"compel inquiries as to the cause. For\neign selling of shares anti a clouded\ninternational outlook were factors of\nuncertainty, but there is no reason\nto doubt the accuracy of the New\nYork Times\u2019s comment that \u201ccon\nindecision of the.stock market\nreflects above all else the mixed\nviews with respect to the extent of\nthe seasonal autumn pick-up in in\ndustry and trade.\u201d\nA number of carefully considered\n\"views\u201d afford the best opinion now\navailable with regard to the coming\nmonths. The review of the National\nCity bank says that \u201cbusinessmen\nlook forward to a good volume of trade\nactivity in the fall, but are conduct\ning their affairs conservatively, and\nthere is little evidence of the boom\npsychology prevalent at this time a\nyear ago.\u201d The City bank's summary\nagrees with most other interpreta\ntions in counting agricultural pros\nperity as the most favorable factor\n*in the business outlook.\nTaking a longer view, the New\nYork Trust company's publication re\nfers to the danger of higher produc\ntion costs. The desirability of a con\ntinually rising living standard for\nworkers is conceded, but it is pointed\nout that rising costs of production\n\"may render wage increases illusory\nand reduce employment opportuni\nties.\u201d- \"Labor must therefore follow\na moderate and patient course in loss\npt markets here and abroad and\ndownward spiral in the standard of\nliving is to be avoided.\"\nTouching on the same theme, the\nAmerican Federation of Labor in its\nmonthly survey says that, with pro\nduction costs increasing and margins\nof profit being reduced, industry must\nincrease production to maintain total\nprofits without raising prices. The\nreview adds that reduced profit mar\ngins point to the importance of in\ncreasing buying power if \u201cundue\u201d\nprice increases are to be avoided.\nThese deductions are in accord with\nwhat the Brookings institution and\nindependent observers have been\nsteadily asserting.\nBut the American Federation of\nLabor goes on to insist that \u201cfurther\nwage Increases\" are necessary to sup\nply the additional buying power that\nwill prevent prices from going higher.\nThis statement overlooks the fact that\nwag\u00ae costs are a major factor in the\nhigher costs which will threaten\nprofits and compel higher prices.\nDoxes are another important factor\nin costs, but raw materials have\ntended to decline since the specula\ntive movement was checked early in\nthe year.\nNew Business Slack\nTn specific Industries the reports of\ncurrent business are interpreted with\nan element of prophecy. As for the\nsteel business the Iron Age says that\nthere is a growing disposition to ques\ntion whether the aggregate volume\nwill be as large as was expected\nearlier in the summer. The machine\ntool industry has orders on hand to\ninsure moderately satisfactory opera\ntions for the remainder of the year.\nBut new business continues slack and\npresent output is being maintained at\nthe cost of a steadily declining back\nlog. In the automobile industry price\nadvances are regarded with apprehen\nsion as a possible check to the volume\nof orders. Yet automobile production,\nlike steel output, continues at a high\nrate for the time of year, the former\nbeing placed in the New York Times\nindex at 155 per cent of normal and\nthe latter at 130 per cent.\nIn wholesale and retail distribution\ncomparisons are made with a volume\nof business abnormally stimulated a\nyear ago by the soldiers' bonus. Yet\ndeclines have occurred that are more\nextensive than would be inferred from\nthe somewhat inconclusive weekly\nsummaries of Dun Bradstreet's re\nview The Federal Reserve bank of\nNew York finds that reporting whole\nsale concerns in that district sus\ntained a decline of 8.2 per cent in\ntheir July sales as compared with a\nyear ago. This was the first decline\nto be reported for a month since May,\n1936, and, while it is easily accounted\nfor by the bonus spending a year ago,\nit means something in terms of the\ngoods that are to be consumed in the\nremainder of the year.\nIn other respects the report is\nmixed, chain stores sales being 6.3\nper cent higher in dollar volume than\na year ago and grocery sales lower.\nIn department stores for the first\nhalf of August there was a 2.2 per\nAnt rise in sales, and increases rang\ning from 3 to 40 per cent in nearly\nall classes of stock on hand. More\nover, dollar volume is figured in cur\nrent prices, and an Increased sales\ntotal may not mean increased dis\ntribution of goods.\nTrade Comparisons\nThe Annalist is therefore justified\nin saying that \"one does not have to\nsearch far to find indications of\nslackening.\u201d A combination of causes\nmay bring a moderate recession in\ngeneral business before present or\nders in tho capital goods industries\nare filled, or there may be some fa\nvorable turn to preserve the present\nlevel of production. A more favor\nfinancial outlook for the rail\n?Uids would help the market for rail\nroad equipment; just now it is said\nthat the threat of the 70-car bill\nwhich waa passed by the United\nStates Senate has made the railroad\nmanagements reluctant to buy loco\nmotives. This is but one way in\nwhich political leadership of a con\nstructively economic kind would im\nprove business and expand national\nIncome to meet the costs Imposed by\ntexes and higher wage levels.\nDiamond Match Earns\n$1,057,100 in Six Months\nNew York, Sept. I\u2014(AP) \u2014Diamond\nMatch company reported consolidated I\nnet Income today for the six months\nended June 30 of $1,057,100 equal to\n87 cents a common share against\n$1,010,100, of 80 cents, a common\nshare in the first half of 1936.\nBastion-Blessing company declared\nan extra dividend nt 25 cents and\nregular quarterly 40 cents payable\nOctober 1 to stock of record Sep\ntemoer 18.\nCONSUMERS\u2019 GOODS\nAPPARENTLY SLOW;\nREASONSJUNTED\nVariety of Data Studied by\nBusiness Analysts\u2014Esti\nmates of Farm Buying\nPower Revised Downward\nNew York, Sept. 2\u2014(AP) \u2014Business\nanalysts studied a variety of statis\ntics today for an explanation of a\nseeming lag in distribution of con\nsumers' goods.\nA July drop in production of boots\nand shoes under last year's figures,\ncurtailment in the woolen and cotton\ntextile industries and diminishing\nyear-to-year improvement in retail\nsales ail pointed to at least a tem\nporary letdown in business activity.\nShoo manufacturers and dealers\nlaid part of the necessity tor cur\ntailing operations to consumer resist\nance to higher prices. Then, too, the\nrecord-breaking production in the first\nmonths of the year built up inven\ntories which the dull summer trading\nfailed to work off.\nIn the woolen textile industry, the\nNew York Wool Top exchange as\nserted in a review of the week, fast\ndiminishing backlogs caused a num\nber of mills to shut down.\nMen\u2019s-Wear Demand Duller\nDemand for men\u2019s-wear fabrics was\nreported duller than it had been for\nsome time. \u201cThe failure of clothing\nsales to come up to expectations,\" the\nreview continued, \"continued to cause\nconcern and led to the belief in some\nquarters that fall business in apparel\nmay be below expectations.\u201d\nRetail stocks were reported heavy\nand collections slow.\nA more-than-seasonal decline in re\ntail trade in rural areas was attrib\nuted to desire by farmers to appraise\nthe outlook for cash income before\nstocking up too heavily.\nEarlier in the summer, with bumper\ncrops in sight, analysts predicted\nheavy sales increases. But since farm\ncrop prices, with the exception of llve\nj stock, have declined more than was\nexpected, downward revision has been\nmade by some observers in estimates\nof farm buying power.\nBRITISH STERLING\nAND FRENCH FRANC\nAGAIN_ CLOSE OFF\nFar Eastern Currencies Also\nDecline Reserve Bank\nReports Engagement of\n$543,000 Gold in India\nNew York. Sept. 3 \u2014(AP) \u2014The\nBritish pound sterling and the French\nfranc lost further ground in terms of\nthe dollar today.\nSterling closed off 14 of a cent,\nwhile the French unit was down .00%\nof a cent. The Netherlands guilder\nand the Belgium belga were un\nchanged. while the Swiss franc was\nup .00% of a cent.\nFar eastern currencies closed down.\nThe Japanese yen was off .2 of a cent,\nthe Shanghai dollar .17% of a cent\nand the Hongkong dollar .04% of a\ncent.\nThe Federal Reserve bank reported\nthe engagement of $543,000 in gold in\nIndia for shipment to New York.\nClosing New York Rates\nGreat Britain in dollars, others in\ncents:\u2014\nGreat Britain demand $4.96, cables\n$4.96, 60-day bills $4.94 13/16; France\ndemand 3.73, cables 3.73; Italy demand\n5.26%, cables 5.26%.\nDemands\nBelgium 16.85; Germany free 40.16:\nregistered 23.00, travel 26.95; Holland\n55.18; Norway 24.92; Sweden 25.57;\nDenmark 22.15; Finland 2.20; Switzer\nland 22.98; Spain unquoted; Portugal\n4.51; Greece .91%; Poland 18.93;\nCzechoslovakia 3.49; Yugoslavia 2.33;\nAustria 18.87 n; Hungary 19.75; Ru\nmania .74; Argentina 33.05 n; Brazil\n8.80%n; Toklo 28.95; Shanghai 29.70;\nHongkong 31.08; Mexico City 27.85;\nMontreal at New York 99.98 7/16;\nNew York at Montreal 100.019/16.\nBANK OF FRANCE\nDROPS DISCOUNT\nLowers Rate From 4 to 3J/2\nPer Cent to Make Loans\nCheaper in Keeping With\nBonnet\u2019s Plan\nParis, Sept. 2\u2014(AP) \u2014The Bank of\nFrance today lowered its discount rate\nfrom 4 to 3% per cent to make loans\ncheaper in keeping with Finance Min\nister Georges Bonnet's plans for re\nbuilding the nation's economic and\nfinancial structure.\nFinancial circles interpreted the\nlowering of the rate fixed August 3\nas meaning the government was re\nturning to a policy of easier money\nand no longer felt obliged to impose\nthe higher rate as a chock on specu\nlation and the flight of capital.\nThe bourse was slightly easier, but\nthis was attributed to uneasiness over\nthe international situation.\nReduction of the discount rate fol\nlowed closely completion of that part\nof Bonnet's reconstruction program\ncarried out under emergency dicta\ntorial powers, which expired August 31.\nThe statement of the Bank of\nFrance indicated the heavy outflow of\ngold which was going on when Bonnet\ntook office had been reduced to a slow\ntrickle. The bank's reserves of 55,-\n717.532.724 francs (about $2,062,000,-\n000) were higher by 378,325 francs\n(about $14,000) than the week before.\nBank Stocks\n(By the Associated Press')\nBid Asked\nBank of Manhattan 201* 81%\nBankara Tr\nBklyn Tr 117 122\nI'm Han Hk Tr 123 126\nChana X\u2019at 46 48\nChern Bk Tr W 111\nCommercial 183 isn\nCont Bl< Tr 1-I\u2019i n-N\nCorn Ex Ilk T Wi \u00abl%\nEmpire Tr 29 30\nFirst Nat (Boston) 18'4 Ml*\nFirst Natl 2180 2220\nQuaranty Tr :ioo 314\nIrving Tr 14% 16%\nManut'ot'ra Tr 49 61\nDo nr 49% Al\nNatl city 11% 43%\nX Y Trust 130 133\nPublic 40% 42%\nTitle <1 T 12'4\nHinde Dauch Paper company de.\ndared a dividend of 50 cents payable\nSeptember 30 to stock of record Sep\ntember 15,\nfffE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 9, 1937\nTRADERS INCREASINGLY BEARISH\nSINCE STOCK DECLINE RESUMED\nThose Who Have Faith in Dow Theory Recall It\nTeaches That Hope for Resumption of a Major\nUptrend Should Be Abandoned When Renewed\nDrop in Rails Is Followed by New Year\u2019s Low in\nIndustrials Estimates of Business Activity Re\nvised Downward\nNew York, Sept, 2 \u2014Traders in the i\nstock market who have faith in the\nDow theory and who recently were\nbullish. increasingly have turned\nbearish since the downtrend in the\nstock market was resumed Monday.\nFrom their viewpoint, the new 1937.\nclosing W for rails' made yesterday\nwas decidedly bearish. According to\nchartists who follow the Dow theory,\nif the resumed decline in rails should\nbe followed by a new 1937 low for in\ndustrials, hopes of an early re\nsumption of the major upward price\nmovement should be abandoned.\nTo go back no further than the\nbeginning of this year. Industrials\nmade their new seven year recovery\nclosing high on March 10 at 194.40.\nThen there was a decline to 165.51 on\nJune 14, followed by a recovery to\n190.02 on August 14. From the last\nnamed date there was a decline to\n175.91, on August 27, followed by two\ndays of recovery and then a resumed\ndecline. Industrials at last night's I\nclosing of 173.08 were down 21.32\npoints from the year's high and only\n7.57 points above the 1937 low made\nin June 14.\nRails made their six-year recovery\nclosing high on March 17 at 64.46.\nThen there was a decline to 50.17\non June 28, followed first by a re- I\ncovery to 55.05 on July 24 and then\na resumed decline to yesterday'#- new\n1937 low of 48.21. Rails are down 16.25\npoints from the year's.high, which, on\na percentage basis, is a much larger\ndecline than has occurred in in\ndustrials.\nSince the middle of August there\nhas been a marked change in the\nsituation and outlook for general\nbusiness activity. Up to two weeks\nago, the consensus was that with\nEXPORTS IN JULY\nBEAT IMPORTS BUT\nBAD YEAR LIKELY\nFavorable Balance Reported\nfor First Time This Year\nbut Unfavorable Annual\nBalance Expected\nWashington, Sept. 2\u2014(AP)\u2014Amer\nican exports exceeded imports during\nJuly, but commerce department offi\ncials reiterated today that the country\nmay have an unfavorable trade bal\nance for 1937 as a whole.\nThe department reported July ex\nports exceeded imports by $1,836,000.\nThis compared with a $14,666,000 ex\ncess of imports in the same month\nlast year.\nFor the first seven months of this\nyear, however, the trade balance\nswung $144,819,000 toward the import\nside, compared with an unfavorable\nbalance of $24,214,000 in the corre\nsponding period of 1936.\nFavorable Balance Unlikely\nFor the country to attain a favor\nable balance for the year, its sales is\nworld markets would have to top pur\nchases by an average of $29,000,000 a\nmonth for the final five months. In\nthe last five months of 1936 the favor\nable balance averaged only $11,000,000\na month.\nAlthough exports customarily are\nheaviest in the fall, when agricultural\nproducts are shipped, officials said it\nis doubtful they could offset the im\nport balance already reported.\nAuthorities expressed satisfaction\nthat two-way trade has increased sub\nstantially. They said this has been\ndue in large measure to operation of\nthe administration's reciprocal trade\nagreements.\nExports aggregated $1,803,829,000 in\nthe first seven months of 1937, an in\ncrease of $468,478,000 over tho period\nlast year. At $1,948,648,000 imports\nwere up $589,083,000.\nBig Increase on Both Sides\nIn July, exports of $267,185,000 com\npared With $180,390,000 in July a year\nago. Imports aggregated $265,349,000\nand $195,056,000 for the same months.\nThe export increase this year was\nattributed in large measure to greater\nshipments of machinery and vehicles,\ncopper, manufactured and semimanu\nfactured iron and steel, gasoline and\nraw cotton.\nImport increases were spread over\na wide range of commodities, includ\ning meat products, fish, vegetable food\nproducts and vegetables, raw silk and\ncrude rubber.\nThe department said both exports\nand imports gained in each of the\nfirst seven months of this year over\nthe corresponding months in 1936.\nSTRENGTH ABROAD\nHELPS U.S. WHEAT\nChicago Market Develops\nInto \u2018Big Board\u2019 Affair, Al\nthough Argentine Rains\nMay Aid Dry Lands\nChicago. Sept. 2\u2014(AP)\u2014The wheat\nmarket developed Into a \"big broad\"\naffair today after a listless start.\nTrade authorities, plaguel by the\nheat and humidity ascribed the firin\nncss in wheat to unexpected strength\nat Buenos Aires and Liverpool, even\nthough rains in the Argentine were\nexpected to prove beneficial to dry\nwheat lands.\nTrade was only spasmodically ac\ntive during the first half of the ses\nsion. but expanded later to a marked\ndegree. Prices advanced 2'\u00abj to 2%\ncents n bushel, but reacted about a\ncent before the close.\nWheat closed firm, 114-2 cents\nalx>vc yesterday\u2019s finish, September\n1.05%-\u2019?*. December 1.07\u2018i-%. May\nLIOH-i*. corn stronger. ad-\nvanced. September 95tj-%. December\n62%-68, May 6*%-%. \"n\u201d 1 up,\nSeptember 30. rye H-H higher, Sep\ntember 81. and lard 15 to 40 cents ad\nvanced.\nArgentine Cotton Exports\nAre Affected by Drouth\nWashington. Sept. 2 \u2014(AP) Ex-1\nports of Argentine cotton during July\nwere reported by the commerce da-\npartmont today to have been the I\nlowest In any month of the past sev- i\neral years. The decrease reflected i\ndrouth conditions. I\npromised bumper crops, the best In\nfive years, business activity already\nat a new high since 1929, would in\nthe autumn make a new all-time high.\nBut then spotty conditions began to\ndevelop in basic industries.\nLarge consumers of raw and\n'tfirisned goods who earlier in the' year'\nfeared further price advances and\naccumulated heavy inventories, be\ngan with the decline which occurred\nin commodity prices In the spring, to\nuse up their inventories. For manu\nfacturers. billings exceeded bookings.\nBacklogs began to melt. New orders\nare not coming in. In some Unes\nthere has been resistance by con\nsumers to rapidly advancing retail\nprices. Estimates of autumn business\nactivity are now being revised down\nward.\nOn top of the foregoing develop\nments in the domestic picture, what\namounted to war broke out in the\nFar East. Within the past 48 hours\ntwo British vessels have been at\ntacked by submarines off the Spanish\ncoast, with Italy suspected as the\nguilty party.\nIn brief, holders of stocks in this\ncountry and abroad appear to have\nreached the decision that having cash\nin hand is better today than being\nlong of stocks.\nStocks opened heavy here this\nmorning, following weakness at Lon\ndon and in other foreign markets,\nwith leaders from 1 to 1% points\nlower. Turnover in the first hour was\n380,000 shares against the recent\nhourly average of less than 100,000\nshares for a five-hour session. At\nthe end of the first hour today, in\ndustrials were down another 2.28\npoints, or 1.31 per cent, with rail\nstocks down 1 point, or 2.07 per cent.\nR. L. BARNUM\nRECENT PROSPERITY\nSEEN AT COST OF\nAUTUMNJUSINESS\nExpected Improvement This\nFall Will Be Less Impres\nsive Than Anticipated, It\nIs Felt\nNew York, Sept. 3\u2014-(AP)\u2014Business\nanalysts, aware that near-term trends\nwill be distorted by the Labor day\nholiday, have trained sights on fail\nprospects and first reports said the\noutlook was only fair to good.\nIn general, opinion Is that although\nthe fail will bring some improvement,\nit may be far less impressive than\nexpected earlier in the summer.\nFor one thing, they say, the un\nusual energy of trade and industry\nduring July and August to some ex\ntent may prove to have been scored at\nthe expense of the autumn months.\nIn any event it is felt the summer\nrate of activity was so brisk as to\nmodify the prospect of sharp gains\nfrom current levels.\nProspects Summed Up\nObservers scanning prospects in\nspecific lines sum up as follows:\nSteel men have begun to question\nthe pace of the fall demand. Current\nguesses are business in light steels\nmay be good and less satisfactory in\nheavy products.\nMotor makers have good hopes\nhigher farm buying power may help\nsales, but some stress higher prices\nmay retard demand.\nFreight carloadings are expected by\ntraffic experts to reach a fall peak of\naround 960,000 cars a week, com\npared with the top of 326.155 in the\nweek of October 17, last year.\nChary of predictions on electric\npower production, utility men point\nout that although well-sustained out\nput is indicated, weekly totals will de\npend on such unpredictable factors as\nweather and the rate of industrial\nconsumption.\nInasmuch as general business will\ntake its cue in large from public buy\ning power two key factors are receiv\ning close scruting: Farm buying pow\ner and rising living costs.\nFarm Price Drops Alter Picture\nIt is recalled that while agricultural\nbuying power is estimated to have\nreached a recovery high on the basis\nof figures for the first half of the\nyear, recent declines in prices of farm\nproducts may alter the picture. Drops\nin wheat, cotton and livestock have\nbeen pronounced.\nHigher living costs have been\nposted owing to rising rents, ad\nvances in clothing prices and higher\nprices for some foodstuffs.\nWhether declines in buying power\nin some regions and higher living\ncosts will retard retail buying during\nautumn months remains to be seen.\nBoston Stock Market\nBoston Sept, 7\u2014(AP)\u2014Following nre the\nsales, high, low and closing prices of\nstocks and bonds traded today on the\nBoston Stock exchange:\nNet\nSale!\" High Low Close Ch'ge\n10 Alles Fish 3 .3 .3\n50 Bos Me 8% B*4 R%\n20 Do pr pf 30 30 30 \u20141\n140 Do pf A ata 10 9 0 \u2014-1\n20 Boston Ed 131 131% 131^\u20142\n\u2022J 5 Boston Elev HO 3914 39%--\n135 Copper Range 11 10% 10%\n50 East Ros Co\n1R East G&F pr pf. Rl RO% 61\n30 East Mass pf 37 37 37\n20 Employers' Group. 20% 20% 20%4-\n10 Gilchrist 12 12 12 +t\n100 Helvetia sOc 50c 30c\n100 isle Koyale 4% 4% 4%\n5 Maine Cen 15 15 15 \u20142\n50 Mass Util 3 3 3\n25 Mergenthaler Lino 38% 38% 38%\n1610 Narraganat Rae. 0% 0%\n1300 Nat Tunnel M 4% 3% 3%\u2014\n97 New Eng T A T. 110% 11H% 11\u00ab%+\n2895 Nor Butte 1 99c 1\n110 Quincy Mng 7 5 6 \u20141 j\n325 Shawmut Assn ct. 13% 13 13 \u20141\n40 Torrington 37% 30% 36%\n40 Union Twist Dr.. 30 29% 30 \u2014l% i\n25 Unit Gas Corp 8 8 R\n125 Unit Shoo Mach 84% 82 82 \u20143\n2200 Utah Metal 1% 1% I%\u2014\n50 Venes Hold 2% 2% 2%\n20 Warren 8 D 38% 37% 37%\u20142%\nUnited States Treasury\nWashington, Sept. 7\u2014Government\nexpenses and receipts for the cur- i\nrent fiscal year through September\n3, compared with a year ago:\nThl. Tear l.a.t Year\nExpen.es 31.333,044,220.3.1 31,000,3311.389.41\nReceipts 913,032,524.00 3 67t.OSOAM.T3i\nDeficit S 42:1,011,703.29 5M.70W13.68 I\nCash Bal. ..32,937.164,014.87 31.850.150.T32.15\nPeoples Drug Stores, inc\u201e reported\nan increase of 1.9 per cent in August\nnet sales to 31.772,365 from 321,738.-\n271 In August last year. For the eight;\nmonths sales totaled 314,545,208 I\nagainst 313,333,343 hl the like period,\na gain of 9.1 per cent. j\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew York Stock exchange... .1,871,150\nSew York Curb exchange 462,000\nBoston Stock exchange...... 29,631\nSTOCK AVERAGES\n30 15 15 60\n(Compiled by the Associated Press)\nln<l. Rails Util. Stks.\nSet change \u2014.47 \u20143.1 \u20141.4\u2014,3A\nTuesday 854 x 31.2 39.1 x 60.2\nPrevious day 911.5 344 404 63.7\nMonth ago 984 39.0 43.4 69.5\nYear ago 914 414 52.9 611.2\n1937 high 1014 49.5 51.0 754\n1937 low 85.5 31.2 39.1 60.2\n1936 high 99.3 434 53.7 724\n1936 lov, 78.4 30.2 43.4 55.7\nMovement In Recent Years\n1932 low 174 8.7 23.9 16.9\n1929 high 1464 153.0 1844 157.7\n192\" low 51.6 054 814 OkS-\nx\u2014New 1937 low.\nNew York, Sept. 7 \u2014(AP)\u2014A new\nforeign war scare today touched off\nthe most severe market break in\nmore than four years and leading\nissues tumbled 1 to 10 points general\nly. There were several wider set\nbacks.\nTraders, back from the holiday,\nwere confronted by news of a threat\nened rupture between Italy and Rus\nsia over the latter\u2019s charges of\n\"piracy\u201d by the former's submarines\nin the Mediterranean.\nStocks were thrown overboard at\nthe opening and offerings attained\nsuch volume in the second hour that\nthe ticker tape lagged three minutes\nbehind floor transactions for a while.\nAlthough volume dwindled later,\nand there were mild recoveries here\nand there, the decline gained headway\nin the final period and numerous is\nsues finished not far from the lowest\nlevels of the session. The ticker was\nagain pressed by heavy offerings on\nthe concluding lap.\nThe Associated Press average of 60\nstocks dropped 3.5 points to 60.2, a\nbottom mark since May 21, last year.\nThe downfall was the largest for a\nsingle day since July 21, 1933. New\nlows for 1937 were established by 384\nindividual shares.\nThe turnover of 1,871,150 shares was\na peak since April 29. The breadth\nof the slump was exemplified by the\nfact 916 issues changed hands. Of\nthese there were 828 declines. 23 ad\nvances and 65 were unchanged.\nIn addition to apprehension over a\npossible European explosion, and fears\nthe Sino-Japanese conflict may be\nI long drawn out with a chance of in\nternational complications in this sec\ntor, the financial district seemed to\nexperience further doubts the ex\npected upturn in fall domestic busi\nness would eventuate to the extern\nexpected.\nThoughts also were present con\nnected with the liklihood that selling\nof American securities held abroad\nmight attain sizable proportions, es\npecially from those countries whose\nmilitary needs would force national\nization of such holdings. It was esti\nmated in some quarters that the Far\nEast bought about $44,000,000 of\nAmerican stocks and bonds in \"935\nand 1936, although part of this\namount has since been liquidated.\nCommission houses with foreign\nconnections, however, reported no un\nusual quantities of stock offered from\nabroad.\nAttention was called by brokerage\ncircles to the \u201cthinness\u201d of the list\non the downside, in several cases re\nlapses of several points occurring be\ntween sales. Bids were withdrawn\nin many Instances and nervous sellers\nwere at the disadvantage of having\nto take whatever they could get.\nUnited States Steel was in the van\nof the retreat, off more than 8 points\nat the worst. It ended down 7% at\n97%. Bethlehem, ex-rights, lost 7%\nat 83%.\nBar silver steady and unchanged at\n44% cents an ounce.\nFollowing is a complete list of final\nstock transactions:\nSales In 100's High Low Close Chg.\nA\n4 Abbott Lab 4* 46 46 \u2014l%\n3 Acme Stl 75 75 75 3\n50 Adams Exp 16% 16 16 1\n3 Addressog 30% 30 30 1\n16 Advance Rumely 2% 1% 1%\n10 Air Reduction 66 62 62%\u2014 4%\n17 Air-Way El Appl 2% 2 2\n27 Alaska .Tuneau 11% 11 II\n68 Alleghany Corp 2% 2% 2%\n1 Alleg pt\u00bb3oww ..25 25 25\n5 Allegheny Steel .30 20% 29% 4\n2 Allen Industries 15% 15 15 \u2014l%\n6AI Chem Dye 230 219 223 3\n6 Allies Mills 20 18% 19 2\n77 Allied Sirs 16% 13% 14 \u20142%\n2 Do pt 73% 70 70 \u20148\n43 Allls-Ch Mfg 60% 5\u00ab% 5\u00ab%\u2014 4%\n513 Do rt 23-32 19-32 19-32\u20148-16\n7 Amal Leather 5 4% 4%\u2014\n9 Amerada Corp 85 83% 83% 2%\n5Am Ag Ch Del 91% 89 89 \u20143%\n4Am Bank Note 23 22% 22%\u2014 1%\n5Am Brake Shoe 53% 52% 52% 2%\n15 Am Can 101 97% 9<%\u2014 3%\n6Am Car Fdy 38% 35% 35% 5%\n2 Do pt 68% 68% 68%\u2014 1%\n25 Am Ch 4 Cable 30 28 2S%\u2014 1%\n2Am Chicle 105% 105 105 \u20142%\n4 Am Colortype 14 13 13\n6 Am Colm Alco 22% 18% IS%\u2014 3%\n5 AmCrystal Sug .26 25 25 \u2014l%\n16 Am En Tiling ..7 6 6\u20141%\n62 Am *F I' 7 6% 6%\u2014\n1 Do $6 pt 32 32 32 8\n21 Do \u00bb7 pt 44% 38 38 \u20145%\n13 Do 2pt 18% 15% 15%\u2014 3%\n2 Am-Haw SS ....15 14% 14%\u2014\n21 Am H t Lea 6% 6\n1 Do pt 39 39 39 \u20141\n4Am Home Pr 44 43% 43%\n6Am Ice 2% 2% 2%\u2014\n3 Do pt 23% 21 21 \u2014t%\n11 Am Interntl 12% 11% 11% 1%\n14 Am Loco 38 35 35 \u20145%\n2 Do pt 101 100 100 \u20144%\n10 Am M t Fdy 18% 17% 1714\u2014 1%\n2 Am M Met 8 7% 7%\u2014\n16 Am Metal 48 43 43 \u20145\n82 Am Pow &Lt 9 7% 8 1\n4 Do $6 pt 56% 55 55 1\n2 Do $5 l't 47% 46% 4614\u2014 2%\n93 Am R